      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed by a second qualified analyst; discrepancies resolved and documented.",
      "rationale": "A second FEA analyst independently reviewed boundary condition definitions, contact pair assignments, and titanium alloy material properties (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, nu=0.34). Two minor discrepancies in load application direction were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Use error risk reduced to Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum solid mechanics with nonlinear geometry (large deformation) and frictional contact is appropriate for pedicle screw construct under quasi-static bending; justified by literature precedent and sensitivity study on contact formulation.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear implicit static analysis with large-deformation kinematics (NLGEOM ON) and augmented Lagrange frictional contact (mu=0.23) selected based on published FDA and DePuy Synthes modeling practices for F1717 constructs. Sensitivity study showed < 1.5% QoI variation between penalty and augmented Lagrange contact formulations. Model form uncertainty quantified and within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for the specific Ti-6Al-4V heat lot; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of as-manufactured test specimens; coefficient of friction from dedicated pin-on-disk tribology tests.",
      "rationale": "Young's modulus, yield strength, and hardening curve obtained from tensile test coupons from the same billet as the test constructs (n=5 coupons). Screw and rod geometry digitized from CMM data with 0.01 mm accuracy. Friction coefficient mu=0.23 ± 0.03 from pin-on-disk testing at physiologically relevant contact pressures. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (n=500) confirming QoI sensitivity within bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 constructs from production lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to nominal geometry; constructs span realistic assembly torque variability.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All constructs inspected by CMM; all within drawing tolerance. Assembly torque varied ± 15% around nominal to capture clinical variability. Sample size sufficient for statistical comparison per ASME V&V 40 guidance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span at least two load levels or fixture configurations to confirm model predictive capability across the operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 standard fixture configuration and a single loading rate (5 mm/min quasi-static). Although the standard protocol was followed rigorously, only one test condition was evaluated. This limits confidence in model extrapolation to non-standard loading configurations. Achieved Gradation 2 is below required Gradation 3; this gap is accepted given the narrow COU scope (standard F1717 only) and is documented as a known assessment gap."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrably derived from or consistent with measured test specimen parameters; traceability matrix documented.",
      "rationale": "A traceability matrix links each FEA input parameter to its experimental source: CMM geometry files, material test reports, load cell calibration records, and fixture drawings. Correspondence confirmed for all 11 constructs. No surrogate or assumed parameters used; all inputs directly measured."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using percent difference and E/uval metric; all QoIs satisfy < 10% difference and E/uval < 1.96.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: mean percent difference 4.2%, E/uval = 0.81. Yield force: mean percent difference 6.7%, E/uval = 1.23. Force at 40 mm: mean percent difference 5.1%, E/uval = 0.97. All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Validation uncertainty (uval) computed from experimental repeatability and simulation input uncertainty combined in quadrature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes of interest and are the same metrics used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and are the primary structural performance indicators cited in the 510(k) submission. These QoIs directly characterize fatigue life precursors and permanent deformation risk. Relevance to COU fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
